[THE CONCEPT MAP IS UPLOADED AS A IMAGE FILE SEPERATELY]

The process begins with a real-world scene, where continuous ambient light, color, and geometry create scene radiance.

An optics and lens system focuses this light, introducing inherent physical distortions, blurring, and aberrations along the way.

The focused light hits an image sensor, which uses a Color Filter Array (CFA) to capture specific wavelengths via the photoelectric effect.

This sensor generates a noisy, continuous analog voltage signal that represents the raw optical data.

An Analog-to-Digital Converter (ADC) samples and quantizes this voltage, transforming it into discrete digital bits.

The resulting output is a linear RAW image file, preserving high bit-depth information directly from the sensor.

An Image Signal Processor (ISP) then runs intermediate transformations like demosaicing to reconstruct full RGB color.

Additional processing steps like noise reduction, white balancing, and tone mapping adapt the image for human perception.

The final output is formatted into standard digital image representations, mapped to specific color spaces like sRGB.

Ultimately, every stage relies on critical dependencies, where hardware quality (optics and sensors) dictates final digital compression and storage efficiency.
